<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-04-04T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-04-04T23:00:00-05:00" n="60" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d60">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 Gemmell, Nina E./12:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Cunningham</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-04-05T12:00:00+08:00">April 5,
                                1930—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received April 5—9:15
                            a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>The following telegram has been sent to the Legation: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“April 5, 10 a.m. Continuing this office’s telegram of March 30,
                                    11 a.m.<note n="80" xml:id="d60fn80">Not printed.</note> The
                                    secretary of the China Inland Mission received last night a
                                    telegram dated Pingsiang April 2nd stating that the Communists
                                    demand for the release of the Porteous party [$]60,000 as
                                    ransom. The telegram was forwarded by Glazier who requested the
                                    mission to wire immediately in Chinese characters accepted or
                                    declined. The secretary stated that it would be inviting trouble
                                    to pay this or any other amount. Repeated to Department, Hankow
                                    and Nanking.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Cunningham</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>